]\n- [2,5]\n- [2,1,5]\n \nConstraints:\n\n1 <= nums.length <= 16\n1 <= nums[i] <= 105\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def countMaxOrSubsets(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\nfrom itertools import combinations\n\nclass Solution:\n    def countMaxOrSubsets(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        max_or = 0\n        count = 0\n        \n        # Calculate the maximum possible bitwise OR of the entire array\n        for num in nums:\n            max_or |= num\n        \n        # Check all subsets\n        for r in range(1, len(nums) + 1):\n            for subset in combinations(nums, r):\n                current_or = 0\n                for num in subset:\n                    current_or |= num\n                if current_or == max_or:\n                    count += 1\n        \n        return count\n```\n\nThis solution calculates the maximum possible bitwise OR of the entire array first. Then, it iterates through all possible non-empty subsets of the array, calculating the bitwise OR for each subset. If the bitwise OR of a subset matches the maximum bitwise OR, it increments the count. The solution uses the `combinations` function from the `itertools` module to generate subsets of different lengths.", "estimated_date": 1634428800000}